      <!-- 10 · LEGAL -->
      <section id="legal">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">Are captive-bred African Grey eggs legal to buy in the USA?</h2>
        <p>Legality is a fair worry with African Greys, and the honest answer is reassuring: because our birds are captive-bred, their eggs are legal to own and transfer within the United States with the right paperwork. African Greys are CITES Appendix I, and we lean into that status rather than dodge it — it's the frame that separates documented breeders from the wild-caught trade we'll never touch.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "captive-bred-cites-appendix-i-egg-documentation.webp"} srcset={IMG + "captive-bred-cites-appendix-i-egg-documentation-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "captive-bred-cites-appendix-i-egg-documentation.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Captive-bred CITES Appendix I documentation accompanying African Grey eggs" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">CITES Appendix I + USDA AWA, in plain English</h3>
        <p>In plain terms, CITES Appendix I is the strictest protection tier, and it makes captive-bred documentation essential — which is exactly why we keep it on every bird. Pair that with our USDA Animal Welfare Act license and you have a paper trail a fake listing simply cannot reproduce.</p>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">What paperwork travels with your birds</h4>
        <p>Documentation follows what we place: captive-bred CITES paperwork, DNA sexing certificates, an avian-vet health certificate, and a hatch certificate with a band number for our chicks. For a broader picture, <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/">our CITES documentation guide</a> walks through each record.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">Never wild-caught — captive-bred USA only</h5>
        <p>Every egg and bird we sell is captive-bred in the USA, full stop — we have never dealt in wild-caught African Greys, and Appendix I is why that line is absolute. Buying documented captive-bred stock is how ethical buyers keep pressure off wild populations.</p>

        <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation — CITES Appendix I history</h6>
        <p>The species moved up to <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES Appendix I</a> at CoP17 — effective January 2017, a tightening from its former Appendix II listing — per the Convention's own records. We reference the source so the status is verifiable, not just stated.</p>
      </section>

